<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>19098</anchor> <rss>sanjivranchod.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Person</taxon> <addr>sanjivranchod</addr>  <route>sanjivranchod.xml</route>   <title>Sanjiv Ranchod</title> <meta name="position">PhD Student</meta><meta name="phd-supervisor">marcelofiore</meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter/> <backmatter><contributions/> <context/> <related/> <backlinks><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>19099</anchor> <rss>2023-10-02.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Entry</taxon> <addr>2023-10-02</addr>  <route>2023-10-02.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>2</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>2023-10-02</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Today I had <link href="sanjivranchod.xml" type="local" title="Sanjiv Ranchod">Sanjiv Ranchod</link>’s first year viva with <link href="jamievicary.xml" type="local" title="Jamie Vicary">Jamie Vicary</link>, as well as the <link href="jms-009U.xml" type="local" title="SANDWICH Seminar">SANDWICH Seminar</link>.</p><p>I am thinking that it would be good to write a blog post about how daily journaling can fit into a successful scientific workflow; it would be good to think a bit more about whether <link href="jms-005P.xml" type="local" title="Forester">Forester</link> can be adapted to more directly serve this use-case.</p></mainmatter> </tree></backlinks> <references/></backmatter></tree>